@NODE "11_makedic" "OwnWords / Making a dictionary"
@NEXT "12_extutil"
@PREV "10_arexx_quit"
@TOC "MAIN"

Making a dictionary
-------------------


The format of the dictionary:

keyword:meaning1[/meaning2/ .. /meaningN]\n

For example:
...
mumus:bugaboo/bogay-man/bugbear
...

  You  can find a dictionary database usually in dBase DBF format, on an IBM
PC.   So  you'll  need some utility to convert it to ascii.  You can use the
LSDBCONV  or  the dbf2asc package (the second one is on the AmiNet).  If you
use  the  dbf2asc  utility  to convert it to ascii, you'll get the following
output:
(if you wrote 58 on the field separator gadget)

...
"mumus":"bugaboo"
"mumus":"bogay-man"
"mumus":"bugbear"
...

  You  need  to eliminate the "-s.  Use a text editor's replace function for
this job.  So, you get something like this:

...
mumus:bugaboo
mumus:bogay-man
mumus:bugbear
...

  At  the  first  step,  you may create the opposite dictionary with the @{"ops" LINK "19_extutil_ops"}
utility, if you need this action.

  Now  you  have  to sort this with the @{"srt" LINK "14_extutil_srt"} util, after sorting, you have to
optimize  the  redundant  keywords  with the @{"opt" LINK "13_extutil_opt"} util.  At last, you need an
index  for  searching,  you  can  generate this with the @{"ind" LINK "15_extutil_ind"} util.  You find
these  utils  in  the  Utils directory.  Finally you have to write the @{"*.dic" LINK "18_dicformat"}
info file, and put the results on a directory somewhere on your HD.

  Now  I am working on a DBF to ascii converter.  I'll finish this work in a
week.

@ENDNODE

